	<paragraphs label="linear-terms">
		<title> Linear Terms </title>

		<p>
			To decide whether a differential equation is linear, we first need to understand what it means for a <xref ref="summary-terms" text="custom">term</xref> to be linear. In this context, linearity refers to how the dependent variable and its derivatives appear in each term.
		</p>

		<p>
			A term is considered <term>linear</term> if:
			<ul>
				<li>It includes only one instance of the dependent variable or one of its derivatives,</li>
				<li>That variable or derivative appears to the power of one,</li>
				<li>It is not inside another function (like <m>\ln(y)</m> or <m>\sin(y)</m>).</li>
			</ul>
		</p>

		<p>
			The <xref ref="summary-coefficients" text="custom">coefficient</xref> of the term doesn‚Äôt affect whether it‚Äôs linear‚Äîeven if the coefficient is a complicated function of the independent variable.
		</p>


		<p>
			Let‚Äôs analyze the linearity of each term in this differential equation:
			<me>
			y\frac{d^5y}{dt^5} + 2t^3\ \frac{d^2y}{dt^2} + \ln\left(\frac{dy}{dt}\right) + y^2 = t^3
			</me>
		</p>

		<p>
			The terms are:
		</p>

		<dl>
			<li>
			<title> <m>\ds y\frac{d^5y}{dt^5}</m> </title>
			<p>
				Nonlinear. This term involves a product of the dependent variable and its derivative, violating the rule that only one can appear in a term.
			</p>
			</li>
			<li>
			<title> <m>\ds 2t^3\frac{d^2y}{dt^2}</m> </title>
			<p>
				Linear. The derivative <m>y''</m> appears by itself and to the first power. The coefficient <m>2t^3</m> does not affect linearity.
			</p>
			</li>
			<li>
			<title> <m>\ds \ln\left(\frac{dy}{dt}\right)</m> </title>
			<p>
				Nonlinear. The derivative <m>y'</m> appears inside a nonlinear function, the natural logarithm.
			</p>
			</li>
			<li>
			<title> <m>\ds y^2</m> </title>
			<p>
				Nonlinear. The dependent variable appears raised to a power other than one.
			</p>
			</li>
			<li>
			<title> <m>\ds t^3</m> </title>
			<p>
				Linear. This term doesn‚Äôt involve the dependent variable or any of its derivatives.
			</p>
			</li>
		</dl>

		<p>
			Let's practice identifying linear and nonlinear terms in other equations.
		</p>

		<example>
			<title> Identify the Linearity of the Terms </title>
			<statement>
			<p>Determine whether each term in the equation is linear or nonlinear:</p>
			<sidebyside>
				<p>
				<m>
					\ds\frac{1}{t}y'' + y^2 + \ln(y') = e^t
				</m>
				<solution>
					<p>
					Focus on the dependent variable, <m>{\color{BurntOrange} y}</m>, and its derivatives.
					<md>
						<mrow>
						\underset{\overline{\text{linear}}}{\frac{1}{t}{\color{BurntOrange} y''}} +
						\underset{\overline{\text{nonlinear}}}{{\color{BurntOrange} y}^2} +
						\underset{\overline{\text{nonlinear}}}{\ln({\color{BurntOrange} y'})} =\ 
						\underset{\overline{\text{linear}}}{e^t}
						</mrow>
					</md>
					</p>
				</solution>
				</p>
				<p>
				<m>
					\ds P^{(6)} + \frac{m P'}{P} = (m - 1)^2
				</m>
				<solution>
					<p>
					Focus on the dependent variable, <m>{\color{BurntOrange} P}</m>, and its derivatives.
					<md>
						<mrow>
						\underset{\text{linear}}{\underline{\color{BurntOrange} P^{(6)}}} +
						\underset{\overline{\text{nonlinear}}}{\frac{m {\color{BurntOrange} P'}}{{\color{BurntOrange} P}}} =\ 
						\underset{\text{linear}}{\underline{(m - 1)^2}}
						</mrow>
					</md>
					</p>
				</solution>
				</p>
			</sidebyside>
			</statement>
		</example>

		<assemblage xml:id="identifying-nonlinear-terms">
			<title> ‚ú≥Ô∏è Identifying Nonlinear Terms </title>
			<p>
			A term is <term>nonlinear</term> if the dependent variable or its derivatives:
			</p>
			<p>
			<ul marker="square">
			<li><p>Are raised to a power other than 1, like <m>y^2</m> or <m>(y')^{-4}</m></p></li>
			<li><p>Appear inside a nonlinear function, like <m>\ln(y)</m> or <m>\sin(y)</m></p></li>
			<li><p>Multiply or divide each other, like <m>y y'''</m> or <m>\frac{y'}{y}</m></p></li>
			</ul>
			</p>
		</assemblage>

